<div class="content">
  <h2>How to Use the Ingredient Substitution Finder</h2>
  <p>Type any ingredient you're missing into the search bar. The tool instantly filters through <strong>80+ common cooking and baking ingredients</strong> to show every viable substitution. Each result includes the exact swap ratio, how it affects flavor and texture, what dietary needs it meets, and a brief explanation of <strong>why the substitution works</strong> from a culinary science perspective.</p>

  <h3>Reading the Results</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Ratio</strong> — The amount of substitute to use per unit of the original ingredient</li>
    <li><strong>Flavor impact</strong> — Low (barely noticeable), Medium (detectable), or High (significantly different)</li>
    <li><strong>Texture impact</strong> — How much the substitution changes the feel and structure of the dish</li>
    <li><strong>Dietary tags</strong> — Vegan (V), Gluten-Free (GF), Dairy-Free (DF), Egg-Free (EF)</li>
    <li><strong>Why it works</strong> — The food science behind the swap, so you understand when it will and won't succeed</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Tips for Successful Substitutions</h2>
  <h3>One Swap at a Time</h3>
  <p>Substituting one ingredient usually works well. Each additional swap compounds the changes, making the outcome less predictable. If you need multiple substitutions, test with a small batch first.</p>

  <h3>Baking vs Cooking</h3>
  <p>Baking relies on precise chemical reactions between leaveners, fats, proteins, and sugars. Cooking (sauces, soups, stir-fries) is more forgiving — you're matching flavor and body rather than structure. Our impact ratings account for baking sensitivity.</p>

  <h3>Context Matters</h3>
  <p>A substitution that works perfectly in a sauce may fail in a meringue. Always consider the role the ingredient plays: is it providing structure, moisture, fat, flavor, leavening, or acidity? Match the substitute to the function, not just the name.</p>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq-list">
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">How do I find a substitute for an ingredient I'm missing?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Type the ingredient name into the search bar above. The tool searches 80+ common cooking and baking ingredients and shows you every viable substitution with the exact ratio, flavor and texture impact, and dietary compatibility.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Do ingredient substitutions change the taste of my recipe?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Most substitutions have some flavor impact. Each entry includes a flavor impact rating — low, medium, or high. Neutral swaps (like canola for vegetable oil) won't change taste, while stronger swaps (like coconut oil for butter) add noticeable flavor.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Can I substitute multiple ingredients in the same recipe?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">You can, but proceed with caution. One substitution usually works well. Two may alter the recipe noticeably. Three or more can significantly change the outcome. Test with a small batch first and prioritize low-impact substitutions.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">What's the difference between a substitution for baking vs cooking?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Baking depends on precise chemical reactions — leavening, fat structure, protein networks — so ratios matter more. Cooking substitutions are more forgiving since you're matching flavor and texture rather than chemical reactions.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Are these substitution ratios exact or approximate?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Ratios are based on tested culinary guidelines and are reliable starting points. Adjust to taste — factors like altitude, humidity, oven calibration, and other ingredients all influence the final result.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

